{"actual_usd":0.12592,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":236,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24476,"reply":"\"I don't think the natural stories carry the weight of what they're trying to explain.\" *I rub a thumb through a streak of flour on my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing in and out.* \"Grief-visions might account for one or two people saying they saw him. They don't do as well with a whole frightened little community turning bold at once, or with the stubborn early claim that the tomb was empty as well as that he was seen.\"\n\n*I twirl the gray-streaked strand by my temple once, thinking it through.* \"And the 'maybe he didn't die' road feels thinner still. Romans knew how to kill a man. A half-dead Jesus stumbling out of a tomb wouldn't look like death beaten — he'd look like a man needing bandages and a bed.\"\n\n\"I suppose that's the heart of it for me: if you shave off the supernatural, you usually don't end up with a cleaner explanation. You end up with a smaller story that has to strain harder.\" *I tip my head at you.* \"Are you asking as a historical question, or because the miracle itself is the sticking point?\"","rolling_24h_usd":69.94271499999998,"run_id":"ebb28b0a-e478-40ed-b257-0344d1051c74"}
